<dl id="n12029e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12029e">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12029e"> 29(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> write O</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Ceux, qui vouloient entrer dans le corps des Druides, devoient en &ecirc;tre dignes par leur vertu, & quelques-uns travailloient &agrave; s&apos;en rendre capables, par un cours de vingt ann&eacute;es d&apos;&eacute;tude, pendant lequel il n&apos;&eacute;toit pas permis d&apos;&eacute;crire la moinde<font color="green">[sic]</font> des le&ccedil;ons qu&apos;on recevoit; il falloit tout apprendre par c&oelig;ur, soit que ce f&ucirc;t pour exercer la m&eacute;moire (&hellip;) ou pour ne pas divulguer les myst&egrave;res. Apr&egrave;s le cours d&apos;&eacute;tude, on subissoit un examen, & l&apos;on n&apos;&eacute;toit admis qu&apos;en r&eacute;citant plusieurs milliers de vers, soit en principes, soit en r&eacute;ponses &agrave; des questions <font color="green">[br>[Those who wanted to enter the corps of Druids needed to be fit for it by their virtue, and some worked hard to prepare themselves by means of a course requiring twenty years of study, during which students were not allowed to write down any aspect of the classes they attended; everything had to be memorized, either in order to exercise their memory (&hellip;) or in order not to divulge the mysteries. At the end of the course on had to take an exam, which consisted in reciting several thousands of verses, in the form of either principles, or answers to questions]</font> <small> M. Sabbathier, <a name="MSAD" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#MSAD"><cite title="source">Dictionnaire pour l'intelligence des auteurs classiques, Grecs et Latins</cite></a> (1773) 492</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
